segments.text: This is an interview with Dana Hefner by Margaret Hefner on April 15, 1990, in Wharton, Texas, concerning the topic of the Vietnam War.
In the interest of accumulating knowledge, I'm asking you to donate this tape to me or to the Texas A&M Oral History Collection in the University Archives.
Is this all right with you?
Yes, it is.
Okay, I'm just going to start by asking you a few questions.
All right.
What was your specific duty in the Air Force, and how did this relate to your perceptions of the war?
Specific duties were munitions maintenance with the 431st Munition Maintenance Squadron, Tui Wa, Vietnam, Republic of Vietnam.
Our specific duties were...
the production of munitions from 22 caliber small arms to 250 to 750 pound bombs, napalm and HE.
We flew support missions for ground support troops.
We flew very few missions, if any, into North Vietnam.
All was done in South Vietnam for support of the troops.
Okay, and when did you join the Air Force, or did you volunteer?
After high school, I went to Del Mar Tech in Corpus Christi for a short period.
The draft was real heavy.
And I figured I would get into the Air Force rather than going to the Army, where possibly I could get a further education.
This was in the latter part of 65 and early 66.
When were you in Vietnam?
What specific, okay, you just said.
The specific dates in Vietnam was from around Easter.
Of 68 to 79, give or take 30 days would accumulate a year.
Okay, and when were you there?
68, okay.
Okay, can you describe the countryside and the village and the base at which you were stationed in Vietnam?
Tuliwala was a brand new Air Force base when I got there.
In fact, it hadn't been completed.
We were right on the beach of the South China Sea, about 165 miles south of Da Nang.
We were bordered on the other side by a mountainous area and some jungle with villages on the outlying perimeter.
Approximately...
12 to 14 miles from the city of Tui Wah, which is a Providence capital.
To what extent and in what ways did you interact with the Vietnamese people?
I had very little dealings with the civilian population as a whole.
We did employ civilians.
to work in the munitions area and on base.
We used them quite a bit in our crews for the building of bombs and rockets and the assembly of 20 millimeter and 7.62 munitions fire.
How were the Vietnamese people and their culture viewed by Americans in the Air Force?
or people you're around?
I'm not real sure about other people.
I viewed their customs and their traditions as very odd.
Never being in an Asian country, I'd never been around Asians.
And they did some funny things.
In fact, we used to laugh a lot
when it came time for a child, they would wash their feet over preference of washing their hands, which I thought was really funny.
Okay.
How do you think, from your experience, the Vietnamese viewed American soldiers and the American people?
I believe that the majority of the Vietnamese that I
encountered were very supportive and very glad to have the Americans there.
They seemed to want their freedom and expected the Americans to help them obtain it.
But you know, there's that minority that we find all over the world.
They were very skeptical.
And what was an average daily routine for you in Vietnam?
An average daily routine?

We split up on shifts where a month at a time we would work nights, usually go to work around 6 o'clock, and get off anywhere from 6 to 7 in the morning, which we enjoyed the night shift because it was so much cooler.
And our day shifts were from around 7 to 7, with elapsing for child time.
A little time off every night.
In what way did you see a war change after the Tet Offensive was launched on January 31, 1968?
I saw a larger movement.
of North Vietnamese moving into the country, and they were being supported very well by communist countries from the weapons that were captured.
There was a demoralization of the American troops somewhat after the Tet Offensive.
because of the step up and the build up of the numbers of people.
Really, as far as politically wise, I didn't see any change in it.
Okay.
The base that you were stationed, was that the base of the TAC during Tet?
Or you were there at that point?
No, I was not.
Okay.
How was President Johnson and his policy of escalation viewed by Americans in Vietnam?
I think as a whole the American G.I.
viewed President Johnson's stand in Vietnam as a patriotic duty.
Our feelings were that we were over there to overthrow communist rule to a sovereign government.
And we believed that our president was trying to do that.
What aspects of careerism in the military did you encounter?
Did you ever see any of that?
No, not really.
What was the morale like among the Americans in Vietnam, like pre and post Tet?
Morale fluctuated quite a bit the whole period I was there.
It was always up and down.
I couldn't see where the Tet had anything to do with it.
It seemed to me like it was a day-to-day struggle.
to accomplish a job that we were sent there for and in hopes to get it done within the period of a year while you're there and get home.
What was the general attitude of Americans toward their commanding officers and duties, and how was this exemplified?
I think that in my squadron,
We were very supportive of our commanding officers.
Accommodation medals were given out for just about everybody that was there in the 431st Munition Maintenance Squadron while I was over there.
Our commanding officers were very sympathetic of the conditions we were living under and the stress.
It was exemplified by our actions in our profession.
Did you see many GI dissidents when you were there?
No, I didn't.
Okay.
In what way or by what means do you think the war could have been won if you felt like the war could have been won?
And how do you feel like that could be accomplished?
I think that there was so many limitations placed upon the American soldiers and the Allied soldiers that were over there.
The Vietnamese and the Viet Cong had no boundaries.
They crossed at will into Cambodia.
Whereas the
GIs and the Allied forces had boundary lines.
And the Vietnamese fought a guerrilla warfare.
You take, for instance, somebody coming into your country, and you know your homeland.
Go up in the Smoky Mountains.
These people that live there can run and hide for months on end.
They strike
And there's no way to strike back.
And I believe the limitations that was put on the American soldier and the allied forces that were there was a tremendous problem.
This was probably the biggest morale falter that there was.
It was way too many limitations.
And I believe the war could have been won
if some of these limitations would have been lifted.
What type of limitations do you mean?
Well, like I say, there are boundaries, for instance.
We were not allowed to go into Cambodia.
We were not allowed to go into any of the Laotian countries.
Or we were not supposed to.
And I think that this restricted our own power.
I think that the American fighting man is probably the best trained.
And probably the highest credit that can be given to him is fighting in this country with the limitations that was forced on him.
How did you and others in Vietnam cope with death, frustration, fear, and boredom?
A lot of it was making up jokes, finding things to do that we found humorous.
For a while, we were stenciling bombs and such that we were sending to a flight line to be flown in sorties.
with stenciled little slogans like this is a Charlie's cook stove on a napalm bomb, or Ho Chi Minh's a Quaker, or turtle mating season from April 19th to March 32nd, and things like this.
We did have...
We did have town leave that we could take, which I didn't find necessary.
But we had several open air movies on base if you weren't too tired to go.
And we drank a lot of hooch.
What was something that you were commanded to do that you found extremely emotionally difficult to cope?
Being in a war zone, I found it unbearable to think that the base cleanliness was such a priority.
Like I say, being right on the South China Sea
The whole compound was sand.
And there was grass seed thrown in from the United States to be planted in the sand.
Well, with the shifting winds and the tides and the torrential rains, the seed never had a chance to even sprout.
So when this was squelched,
They decided that instead of trying to grow grass, that we would rake the sand and keep it nice and level.
Another thing was pulling KP.
Many times we had to pull KP and still work a 12-hour shift.
And like I say, we did employ Vietnamese civilians on base that could have worked KP.
Instead it was sold.
So it was very difficult to put up with such nonsense.
Now, and what exactly, what exactly is KP?
That is kitchen potholes.
Oh.
That's where you go in and peel potatoes or wash dishes and straighten up mess off.
What type of response did you receive from the American public as a whole when you came back from Vietnam?
As a whole, I felt the American public was very offish.
I think the American public was told things that weren't true.
Very, very, very few times did I ever have anyone
congratulate me for the effort that I put while I was over there.
Most of the time they would add, oh, you were in Vietnam and let it go at that.
My family was very supportive.
My nieces, nephews, my mother, my father, all my brothers and sisters, aunts and uncles.
But as a whole, the general public was very bold.
How has your perception of patriotism and service to your country changed after Vietnam, and why did it change?
If it changed at all, I believe I became more patriotic.
I think that being in a country such as Vietnam and seeing the tragedies
and of people being so suppressed that my patriotism grew deeper.
I would never, I would never ever want to see my children or any descendants of this country have to face what those people in Vietnam did.
In your opinion, what were some major military mistakes that could have been avoided?
I'm not a military leader, and I never claimed to be.
There's mistakes made in every conflict or war.
And if they could have been avoided, I believe they would have.
Everybody is doing mistakes.
And hopefully, if we ever have to go to another country to support what we believe in, in democracy, that those mistakes could be corrected, if there was any mistakes made.
I feel that some of the rules could have been changed to help support the military personnel that was over there, not only the United States.
We had South Koreans there, and we had Australians, and these people fought hard.
In what way did your experience affect your attitude, beliefs, and actions when it was time to carry on an ordinary life in the States?
Probably when I came back, what I mostly thought of was classes of people that are in our country.
whether it be for economic reasons or educational reasons.
I would love to see this corrected, if at all possible.
Any time a person is suppressed, it not only affects themselves and their immediate family,
but it affects all people.
If you had to tell someone of the AIDS generation anything that you learned from your experience in Vietnam, what would it be?
To always keep the attitude.
That no matter how much freedom you do have, that you can lose it.
And that you would always stay on your toes and stay abreast of everything that is going on.
Never, never ever give up your freedom.
Okay, well thank you very much, Dana.
Certainly.
